LiDAR Forest Modeling

set up

# packages
library(lidR)   # lidar data
library(terra)   # spatial data analysis
library(tidyverse)  # organization and manipulating data
#Create LAScatalog object from MKRF las tiles
cat_afrf <- readLAScatalog("data/LAS")

# Quality Check
las_check(cat_afrf) #check the LAS object

# examine the structure and metadata of the LAScatalog object
str(cat_afrf)

# plot
plot(cat_afrf)

#Examine single .las tile 
tile_1_afrf <- readLAS("data/LAS/AFRF_Tile1.las")

# deep inspection of one individual tile
las_check(tile_1_afrf)

DEM

#Create DEM
dem_afrf <- rasterize_terrain(cat_afrf, 
                              2, # 2 meter spatial resolution
                              tin())   # interpolation method

#Create color palette
col_1 <- height.colors(50) 

#Plot DEM using color palette
plot(dem_afrf, col = col_1) #plot in 2D

Figure 1: Digital Elevation Model (DEM) of the Alex Fraser Research Forest

Normalization

#define LAScatalog engine options - Set output folder
opt_output_files(cat_afrf) <- paste("data", "/Normalized/norm_afrf_{ID}", 
                                             sep = "")

#normalize all tiles in cat_mkrf with the DEM 
cat_afrf_norm  <- normalize_height(cat_afrf,  # original elevation
                                    dem_afrf)    # ground elevation

# re-read normalized tiles into a new catalog
cat_afrf_norm <- readLAScatalog("data/Normalized")

# 
opt_filter(cat_afrf_norm) <- "-drop_z_below 0 -drop_z_above 55"

Canopy Height Model (CHM)

# generate canopy height model at 2m resolution using the P2R algorithm
chm_afrf <- rasterize_canopy(cat_afrf_norm, 
                             res = 2, 
                             algorithm = p2r())

# plot CHM
plot(chm_afrf)

Figure 2: Canopy Height Model (CHM) of the Alex Fraser Research Forest

Plots

#read 'Plot_Table.csv'
plot_table <- read.csv("data/Plots/Plot_Table.csv")

#define plot radius
radius <- 10

#for loop to extract multiple plots
#run the loop until i = the number of rows in 'plot_table' (20)
for(i in 1:nrow(plot_table)){ 
  
  #extract plot center
  plot_cent <- c(plot_table$X[i], plot_table$Y[i]) 
  
  #clip plot from norm_cat_las
  plot_las <- clip_circle(cat_afrf_norm, plot_cent[1], plot_cent[2], radius) 
  
  #output directory as string
  output_file <- paste("data/Plots/AFRF_Plot_", i, ".las", sep = "") 
  
  #write'MKRF_Plot_i' to output dir.
  writeLAS(assign(paste("AFRF_Plot_", i, sep = ""), plot_las), output_file) 
}

Area Based Metrics

# initialize empty dataframe to store plot level lidar metrics
afrf_plot_metrics <- data.frame()

# loop through each plot to calculate statistical summaries 
for(i in 1:nrow(plot_table)){
  
  # read individual plot las file using only first returns and points above 2m
  plot <- readLAS(paste("data/Plots/AFRF_Plot_", i, ".las", sep = ""),
                  filter = "-keep_first -drop_z_below 2")
  
  # calculate standard suite of metrics for the current plot
  metrics <- cloud_metrics(plot, .stdmetrics)
  
  # Add the Plot ID 
  metrics$Plot_ID <- i
  
  # append current plot metrics to the master dataframe
  afrf_plot_metrics <- rbind(afrf_plot_metrics, metrics)
}

# export the compiled plot metrics to a csv
write.csv(afrf_plot_metrics,
          "data/Plots/afrf_plot_metrics.csv",
          row.names = FALSE)

merge data

# Read in field data and calculated lidar metrics
plot_table <- read_csv("data/Plots/Plot_Table.csv")
afrf_metrics <- read_csv("data/Plots/afrf_plot_metrics.csv")

# merge field observations and lidar metrics into a single dataframe
data_table <- plot_table %>%
  full_join(afrf_metrics, by = "Plot_ID")

# inspect column names
colnames(data_table)

Model 1: Dominant Height

  • Initial Variables: zq90, zq95, zmean, zmax, zentropy, zskew, zkurt
  • Equation: Dominant Height = 0.75(zq95) + 10.84(zentropy) + 0.53
  • Adjusted \(R^2\): 0.826
# Create a "blank" model for Dominant Height
model_h <- lm(Dominant_Height ~ 1, data = data_table)

# different variables that may represent dominant height 
add1(model_h, ~ zq90 + zq95 + zmean + zmax + zentropy + zskew + zkurt, test = "F")

# ZQ95 was one of the most significant predictor - add to model
model_h <- lm(Dominant_Height ~ zq95, data = data_table)

# zentropy was the most significant predictor with zq90 - add to model
model_h <- lm(Dominant_Height ~ zq95 + zentropy, data = data_table)

#No additional variables were significant, so we can stop building our model

#Get the summary of the final model
summary(model_h)

#Plot our predicted volume against our measured volume
plot(Dominant_Height ~ model_h$fitted,
     data = data_table,
     xlab = 'Predicted',
     ylab = 'Measured')
abline(0,1) #Adds a one to one line

#Get the coefficients to our model
model_h$coefficients

Figure 3: Predicted vs.Measured Dominant Height (m)

Model 2: Above ground biomass (AGB)

  • Initial Variables: zq95, zmean, zentropy, zskew, zkurt, zq50, pzabovezmean, zsd, zpcum6, zpcum9
  • Equation: AGB = 13024.398(zq95) + 21328.972(zkurt) + 5417.541(zpcum9) 740401.750
  • Adjusted R\(^2\) 0.6906
# Create a "blank" model for Dominant Height
model_agb <- lm(Total_AGB ~ 1, data = data_table)

# different variables that may represent above ground biomass 
add1(model_agb, ~ zq95 + zmean + zentropy + zskew + zkurt + zq50 + 
       pzabovezmean + zsd + zpcum6 + zpcum9, test = "F")

# update model with zq95 as an significant first predictor
model_agb <- lm(Total_AGB ~ zq95, data = data_table)

# add zkurt as the second predictor
model_agb <- lm(Total_AGB ~ zq95 + zkurt, data = data_table)

# dd zpcum9 as the third predictor
model_agb <- lm(Total_AGB ~ zq95 + zkurt + zpcum9, data = data_table)

#No additional variables were significant, so we can stop building our model

#Get the summary of the final model
summary(model_agb)

#Plot our predicted volume against our measured volume
plot(Total_AGB ~ model_agb$fitted,
     data = data_table,
     xlab = 'Predicted',
     ylab = 'Measured')
abline(0,1) #Adds a one to one line

#Get the coefficients to our model
model_agb$coefficients

Figure 4: Predicted vs.Measured Total Above Ground Biomass (kg/ha)

Wall to wall calculations

# creates a multi layer SpatRaster (where each layer is a metric)
#metrics_afrf <- pixel_metrics(cat_afrf_norm, 
                       #       .stdmetrics, 
                       #       2)  # 2m res
# export the multi-layer metric stack to a GeoTIFF 
#writeRaster(metrics_afrf, "data/afrf_metrics_stack.tif", overwrite = TRUE)
# read in
metrics_afrf <- rast("data/afrf_metrics_stack.tif")

# Model 1: Dominant Height
# subset specific predictors: zq95, zentropy
h_vars <- terra::subset(metrics_afrf, c("zq95", "zentropy"))
# use predict() to map model_h coefficients onto the raster layers
# calculates: 0.53 + (0.75 * zq95) + (10.84 * zentropy)
dom_height_map <- predict(h_vars, model_h)
# plot 
plot(dom_height_map)

# Model 2: Above Ground Biomass (AGB)
# subset specific predictors: zq95, zkurt, zpcum9
agb_vars <- terra::subset(metrics_afrf, c("zq95", "zkurt", "zpcum9"))
# use predict() to map model_agb coefficients onto the raster layers
# calculates: -740401.750 + (13024.398 * zq95) + (21328.972 * zkurt) + (5417.541 * zpcum9)
agb_map <- predict(agb_vars, model_agb)
# plot
plot(agb_map)
